{
  "texts": [
    "Each block of conditions is ordered from weaker to stronger conditions.",
    "x ∈♦ i Y iff ∀x ′ ⊑ x ∃y ′: x ′ R i y ′ and y ′ ∈ Y; 4.",
    "M, x ⊩ ♢ i φ iff ∀x ′ ⊑ x ∃y ′: x ′ R i y ′ and M, y ′ ⊩ φ (see Figure 2.13, right).",
    "x x ′ ∀ ∃ y ′ ⊩ ♢ i φ ⊩ φ x x ′ y ′ y ′′ ∀ ∃ ∃ ⊩ ♢ i φ ⊩ φ Figure 2.13: the semantic clause for ♢ i, without (left) and with (right) the R-down condition.Although unfamiliar, the clause for ♢ i is quite intuitive: for whatever sense of 'possible' is at issue, the clause says that x forces that φ is possible iff for every refinement x ′ of x (think of this as the forcing part), x ′ has access to a state that forces φ, or if we are not assuming R-down, then x ′ has access to state that can be refined to force φ (think of this as the possibility part).It is useful to know shortcuts for thinking about sequences of modal operators involving diamonds.",
    "Since ♢i 1... ♢ in φ is equivalent to ¬□ i 1... □ in ¬φ, we have M, x ⊩ ♢ i 1... ♢ in φ iff ∀x ′ ⊑ x ∃y ′ 1,..., y ′ n: x ′ R i 1 y ′ 1... y ′ n-1 R in y ′ n and ∃y ′′ n ⊑ y ′ n: M, y ′′ n ⊩ φ.Over standard frames satisfying R-down, we can simplify this further as follows.Fact 2.44 (Iterated Modalities)."
